│ Specifically:\n- FirstInsert is computed as the earliest insertelement in     │
│ program order\n- LastInsert is computed as the latest insertelement\n- The    │
│ pass then sets the IRBuilder insertion point to LastInsert:\n                 │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert);\nThen it proceeds to gather/shuffle and   │
│ rebuild the chain. If the newly created shufflevector or interim values are   │
│ inserted at LastInsert, but they are used by instructions that appear before  │
│ LastInsert (e.g., previous insertelements or other users), the new            │
│ definitions will not dominate their uses. This can cause the verifier error.  │
│ To guarantee dominance of the generated values across the entire rebuild, the │
│ insertion point should be set to the first insertelement of the chain         │
│ (FirstInsert), ensuring that newly created values dominate all subsequent     │
│ uses in the chain.\n\nGiven the reproducer, SLP emits a shufflevector using a │
│ vector (%4) that is created later because Builder was set to the last insert. │
│ The mismatch places the use before the definition in some CFG paths,          │
│ triggering the verifier.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:               │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n- Lines: 16806-16812\n-      │
│ Change: Set the IRBuilder insertion point to FirstInsert (the earliest        │
│ insertelement) instead of LastInsert when starting the rebuild of the         │
│ buildvector chain.\n\nSuggested replacement:\nCurrent code:\n                 │
│ sort(ShuffledInserts[I].InsertElements, isFirstInsertElement);\n              │
│ InsertElementInst *FirstInsert = ShuffledInserts[I].InsertElements.front();\n │
│ InsertElementInst *LastInsert = ShuffledInserts[I].InsertElements.back();\n   │
│ ...\n  Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert);\n\nReplace                         │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert); with:\n                                   │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(FirstInsert);\n\nThis ensures that any newly created   │
│ shuffle/buildvector instructions dominate all subsequent insertelement        │
│ instructions and their users.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by       │
│ inserting newly generated shuffle/buildvector instructions too late in the    │
│ insertelement chain, violating dominance. By moving the insertion point from  │
│ LastInsert to FirstInsert before rebuilding, we ensure definitions are placed │
│ early enough to dominate all uses within the chain, fixing the verifier error │
