│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The verifier reports a dominance violation: an insertelement does not         │
│ dominate all uses, and the error shows a shufflevector using the vector built │
│ via insertelement. This is a classic symptom of IR being created with a wrong │
│ insertion point so that a use is placed before its definition in the control  │
│ flow. Given the crash happens right after slp-vectorizer runs and at the      │
│ verifier, the first transformation creating the bad IR is within SLP's        │
│ emission of shuffles/buildvectors.                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The log shows the IR ends up with a sequence:                                 │
│ - %4 = insertelement <2 x float> <poison, 0.0>, float %0, i32 0               │
│ - %2 = shufflevector <2 x float> %4, <2 x float> <0.0, poison>, <2 x i32> <2, │
│ 0>                                                                            │
│ Verifier says %4 "does not dominate all uses" with the use highlighted as %2, │
│ implying %2 is located in a block that precedes (doesn't post-dominate) where │
│ %4 was inserted. This points at incorrect Builder insertion point management  │
│ during SLP's rebuild of insertelement/shuffle chains.                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In SLPVectorizer.cpp, the code that rebuilds buildvector chains after         │
│ recognizing insertelement sequences is in the section around                  │
│ performExtractsShuffleAction and the subsequent rebuild. Specifically:        │
│ - FirstInsert is computed as the earliest insertelement in program order      │
│ - LastInsert is computed as the latest insertelement                          │
│ - The pass then sets the IRBuilder insertion point to LastInsert:             │
│   Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert);                                         │
│ Then it proceeds to gather/shuffle and rebuild the chain. If the newly        │
│ created shufflevector or interim values are inserted at LastInsert, but they  │
│ are used by instructions that appear before LastInsert (e.g., previous        │
│ insertelements or other users), the new definitions will not dominate their   │
│ uses. This can cause the verifier error. To guarantee dominance of the        │
│ generated values across the entire rebuild, the insertion point should be set │
│ to the first insertelement of the chain (FirstInsert), ensuring that newly    │
│ created values dominate all subsequent uses in the chain.                     │
│                                                                               │
│ Given the reproducer, SLP emits a shufflevector using a vector (%4) that is   │
│ created later because Builder was set to the last insert. The mismatch places │
│ the use before the definition in some CFG paths, triggering the verifier.     │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                       │
│ - Lines: 16806-16812                                                          │
│ - Change: Set the IRBuilder insertion point to FirstInsert (the earliest      │
│ insertelement) instead of LastInsert when starting the rebuild of the         │
│ buildvector chain.                                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested replacement:                                                        │
│ Current code:                                                                 │
│   sort(ShuffledInserts[I].InsertElements, isFirstInsertElement);              │
│   InsertElementInst *FirstInsert = ShuffledInserts[I].InsertElements.front(); │
│   InsertElementInst *LastInsert = ShuffledInserts[I].InsertElements.back();   │
│   ...                                                                         │
│   Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert);                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ Replace Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert); with:                             │
│   Builder.SetInsertPoint(FirstInsert);                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures that any newly created shuffle/buildvector instructions dominate │
│ all subsequent insertelement instructions and their users.                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is caused by inserting newly generated shuffle/buildvector          │
│ instructions too late in the insertelement chain, violating dominance. By     │
│ moving the insertion point from LastInsert to FirstInsert before rebuilding,  │
│ we ensure definitions are placed early enough to dominate all uses within the │
│ chain, fixing the verifier error and preventing the abort.                    │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
